title known_hosts folded into the tooling, not just the prose
prompt Keaton, asked "what next," chose closing the smaller --harden-home gaps: fold the known_hosts fix into the witness script, and scope a full private-$HOME.
think the known_hosts fix had only ever been applied by hand, live, in an earlier turn -- the actual generator script and the harden witness never learned it. Folded it into both: tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish now runs ssh-keyscan for github.com and codeberg.org into a jail-local .ssh/known_hosts_jail on every run (always refreshed, since a stale host-key entry is a real if unlikely risk), writes .git/ssh_config_urbit naming both the identity files and the new known_hosts file, and wires git itself -- core.sshCommand, gpg.program, user.signingkey, commit.gpgsign -- so nothing is left to configure by hand afterward.
think hit the same Rish \" -escape gap a third time this project, this time inside the GPG wrapper's own exec gpg "$@" line -- caught it before running, since the pattern is now familiar, and used the dquote.txt fixture join instead. Also hit a second, new Rish gap: a multi-line list literal mixing bare strings and join expressions failed to parse (ExpectedValue) -- worked around with the already-proven per-line let-then-list-of-names pattern cursor_jail_macos.rish already uses, rather than fighting the list-literal syntax further.
think validated the whole rewritten generator in an isolated /tmp scratch repo before touching the real one -- copied the script, its fixtures, GLOW_PROFILE.bron, and rishi itself; ran it twice to confirm idempotency (second run left existing keys alone, refreshed only the SSH comment and the repo-local config, no duplication); inspected every written file (ssh_config_urbit, gpg.sh, known_hosts_jail) and the resulting git config by hand before trusting it; deleted the scratch tree afterward.
think folded the known_hosts finding into tools/cursor_jail_macos_harden_witness.rish itself as a named, mechanically-checked refuse-witness (denies ~/.ssh/known_hosts) and a conditional permit-witness (the jail-local known_hosts_jail stays readable, skipped gracefully if the generator has not run yet) -- ran it in this actual jailed window afterward and, this time, every check genuinely passed (not a false positive from the earlier-named nested-sandbox_apply limitation; the checked files are real and the results matched them), a good live confirmation alongside the documented, still-real limitation that self-testing from inside a jail is not guaranteed to work.
think simplified SOURCE.md Step 8 and the macOS guide's own prose to match: the long manual cat-heredoc-and-three-git-config-lines sequence is gone, replaced by one sentence naming that the script now does all of it.
obs closes a real gap cleanly: before this, the known_hosts fix existed only as something this specific session had done by hand and written about -- a fresh clone, or Keaton on a different Mac, would have hit the exact same Host key verification failed surprise with no automated fix waiting for them. Now the one script that already handles everything else handles this too.
